 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: alarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nImportant classification guidelines:\n\n**Reminders vs Alarms:**\n- \"Reminder\" requests should be classified as 'calendar_set', NOT 'alarm_set'\n- Reminders are typically associated with calendar events and tasks\n- Alarms are typically for wake-up times or simple time-based alerts without specific task context\n- If the text mentions \"reminder\" or implies remembering to do something at a specific time/date, use 'calendar_set'\n\n**News vs Weather queries:**\n- Phrases like \"what is going for tomorrow\", \"what is going on\", or \"what's happening\" refer to NEWS queries about current events, NOT weather queries\n- The word \"going\" in this context means \"happening\" or \"occurring\" (events/news), not weather conditions\n- Weather queries typically include explicit weather-related terms like \"temperature\", \"rain\", \"sunny\", \"forecast\", \"climate\", \"cold\", \"hot\", etc.\n- News queries ask about events, happenings, or what's occurring in the world or on a particular day\n\n**General approach:**\n- Pay close attention to the intent behind colloquial or informal phrasings that may be ambiguous\n- Look for key indicator words that signal the specific category\n- Consider the context and purpose of the request, not just individual words\n- Analyze the text carefully to determine the user's true intent before classifying"
 },
